@article{Lee2015,
abstract = {The laser wakefield acceleration [1] by a high power laser pulse and a plasma has attracted lots of attention in recent years as it can generate quasi-monoenergetic high-energy electron beams [2–5] and it may be used for a compact x-ray source on a table-top scale [6–10]. In the laser wakefield acceleration, plasma electrons can be self-injected into the acceleration phase of the wake wave and they are accelerated with an extremely high gradient in the longitudinal direction. In addition to the longi-tudinal acceleration, the wake wave also gives an ultra-strong focusing force in the transverse direction. As a result, the accelerated electrons execute the betatron oscillations which can produce the betatron radiation. The radiations with shorter wavelengths can be generated with higher e-beam energies and larger betatron oscillation amplitudes for a given plasma den-sity. In general, however, the plasma density is already deter-mined by the laser pulse duration for resonant excitation of the wake wave (i.e. $\tau$ $\lambda$ ≈ c / p with the plasma wavelength $\lambda$ p and c is the light speed in free space) and the electron beam energy is mainly limited by the available laser power. Therefore, if the betatron oscillation amplitude can be increased somehow, it will provide an important way for generation of shorter wave-length radiations, especially in the hard x-ray regime. In this paper, we propose a new method to increase the betatron oscillation amplitude by off-axis laser alignment to a capillary plasma waveguide. It is common knowledge that the capillary plasma waveguide has been used only for optical guiding and electron acceleration [5], where the transverse plasma density profile is nearly parabolic, but recently the study for enhanced betatron oscillation motion using a cor-rugated guiding channel was discussed [11]. In their method, however, they simply assumed an ideal plasma density pro-file for pure theoretical studies and it will be very 